# Writing Standard

## What good acceptance criteria look like

Good acceptance criteria:
- Describe the expected result
- Use measurable or observable language
- Avoid ambiguity
- Stay within the scope of the issue
- Are concise enough to review quickly
- Can be validated without needing tribal knowledge

## What weak acceptance criteria look like

Weak criteria fail because they do not define what a reviewer should observe to confirm completion.

Examples of weak criteria:
- "Works as expected."
- "Bug is fixed."
- "Implement the change."
- "Update the UI."
- "Handle errors."
- "Make it better."
- "Refactor complete."

---

# Formats

Use one of the two formats below. Choose based on the nature of the issue.

## Format A: Given / When / Then

Use for user-facing behavior, workflows, interaction changes, and API behavior.

```text
Given [starting context]
When [action occurs]
Then [expected observable outcome]
```

## Format B: Checklist

Use for technical tasks, migrations, infrastructure changes, and multi-step operations.

```text
- [ ] [Observable condition 1]
- [ ] [Observable condition 2]
- [ ] [Category-specific checklist items from matching CAT rule — see Category-Binding Gate above]
- [ ] 📖 Documentation updated (README / docs folder) if behavior changed
```

---

# Markers on Every Issue

- **💣 at the top** of every issue/prompt (acknowledges rules were loaded — see [core.mdc](core.mdc))
- **📖 next to the documentation-update AC item**
- **💥 at the end** of every output (acknowledges rules were followed)
- After completion, issues must be marked **Done** in Linear (not just PR merged — see [agents.mdc](agents.mdc) § Issue-Driven Work).
